      <hedline>
        <hl1>What Would the Founders Say?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rev L Alexander Harper letter on Michael Novak's Sept 4 article cites distinction between helpful and harmful functions of religion in public discourse</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Novak (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) rightly noted our country's debt to the Jewish faith and language about God. Unfortunately, he tied all this to his familiar, unconstitutional proposal for school prayer drawn from language of the Declaration of Independence.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Michael Novak (Op-Ed, Sept. 4) rightly noted our country's debt to the Jewish faith and language about God. Unfortunately, he tied all this to his familiar, unconstitutional proposal for school prayer drawn from language of the Declaration of Independence.</p>
        <p>Far more important than school prayer is distinction between helpful and harmful functions of religion in public discourse. It was harmful, for example, to mandate belief in God for citizenship, as the Pilgrims first did in Massachusetts.</p>
        <p>On the other hand, it is helpful in a pluralistic society to affirm the (God-given) worth of all people, whatever their views, to gain humaneness, compassion, patience and flexibility in public policy in pursuit of justice and help for the disadvantaged. I know of no major religious community that does not foster those, when rightly understood.</p>
        <p>(Rev.) L. ALEXANDER HARPER  Norwalk, Conn., Sept. 4, 2000</p>
      </block>
